# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: the-oaks-elgin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The **A96** is a major road in the north of Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] It runs generally west/north-west from Aberdeen, bypassing Blackburn, Kintore, Inverurie, Huntly, Fochabers and Forres, and running through Keith, Elgin and Nairn.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The road terminates at the A9 outside Inverness.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The road begins at Mounthooly roundabout, just north of Aberdeen city centre.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] It then exits Aberdeen to the North West, meeting the A92 at the Haudagain Roundabout, a notoriously busy junction.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] It then passes Bucksburn, and has a junction with Aberdeen Airport.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The road is then dual carriageway until Inverurie, where it becomes single carriageway.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The route then connects up Huntly, Keith, Fochabers, Elgin, Forres & Nairn before terminating on the A9 at Inverness.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The A96 has been improved with the addition of bypasses in the 1980s/1990s for Auldearn, Forres, Lhanbryde, Huntly & Inverurie.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The road has been dualled between Inverurie & Aberdeen and several short overtaking lanes exist on the route.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] There are also short stretches of the route that have been widened and realigned to improve traffic flow and overtaking opportunities.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] Debate about a new section of road to bypass Fochabers took place for a number of years.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] When the new bridge was built over the River Spey (in about 1970), it was built to be in line with a possible northern route.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The bypass is to the north of Fochabers and south of Mosstodloch, construction started on 2 February 2010 and was opened in January 2012.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The road still passes through many major towns on the route, namely Elgin, Nairn and Keith.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The A96 has a poor safety record in the substantial single carriageway section, and the road has topped polls to find the most unpopular roads in Scotland on more than one occasion.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The A96 was formerly part of the Euroroute system, of route E120 which ran in a circular route between Inverness, Aberdeen, Dundee and Perth.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] A new bridge called the Inveramsay Bridge was constructed on the A96 northwest of Inverurie.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] This bridge goes over the Aberdeen-Inverness railway line instead of under it like the former one.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The former bridge was not wide enough for two tall vehicles to fit under it so traffic lights were put in place, but caused serious congestion during peak hours.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] In 2016, the Scottish Government announced plans to upgrade the A96 road to a dual carriageway by 2030, at a cost of £3 billion.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] The project would include dualling the 88 miles (142 km) of the A96 that is not dual carriageway between Aberdeen and Inverness.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] An 18-mile (29-kilometre) section of the A96 between Inverness and Auldearn that will bypass Nairn will be the first section of the A96 to be dualled.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] Plans to dual the A9 and A96 have been criticised by Patrick Harvie of the Scottish Greens, who has said the plans are incompatible with the Scottish Government's climate initiatives.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] Concerns have also been raised over the loss of ancient woodland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] A cycle path has been built between Kintore and Port Elphinstone.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/a96-road] In October 2021, work began to build a shared cycle and footpath along the road between Lhanbryde and Fochabers.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles is the eldest son of Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was born during the reign of his maternal grandfather, King George VI, and became heir apparent following his mother's accession in 1952.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was created Prince of Wales in 1958 and his investiture was held in 1969.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was educated at Cheam School and Gordonstoun, and later spent six months at the Timbertop campus of Geelong Grammar School in Victoria, Australia.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] After completing a history degree at the University of Cambridge, he served in the Royal Air Force and the Royal Navy from 1971 to 1976.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He married Lady Diana Spencer in 1981 and they had two sons, William and Harry.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles and Diana divorced in 1996 after years of estrangement and well-publicised extramarital affairs.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Diana died the following year from injuries sustained in a car crash.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 2005, Charles married his long-time partner, Camilla Parker Bowles.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] As heir apparent, Charles undertook official duties and engagements on behalf of his mother and represented the United Kingdom on visits abroad.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He founded the Prince's Trust in 1976, sponsored the Prince's Charities and became patron or president of more than 800 other charities and organisations.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He advocated for the conservation of historic buildings and the importance of traditional architecture in society, and in that vein generated the experimental new town of Poundbury.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] An environmentalist, Charles supported organic farming and action to address climate change during his time as manager of the Duchy of Cornwall estates, earning him awards and recognition.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He has also been a prominent critic of genetically modified food, and has drawn scrutiny for his support of alternative medicine.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He has authored or co-authored 17 books.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles became king upon his mother's death in 2022.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] At the age of 73 he was the oldest person to accede to the British throne, after having been the longest-serving heir apparent and Prince of Wales in British history.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Significant events in his reign have included his coronation in 2023, his cancer diagnosis in 2024 which temporarily suspended planned public engagements, and the removal of his brother Andrew's remaining titles, styles, and honours in 2025.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles was born at 9:14 pm on 14 November 1948 by caesarean section at Buckingham Palace, during the reign of his maternal grandfather, King George VI.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was the first child of Princess Elizabeth, Duchess of Edinburgh (later Queen Elizabeth II), and Philip, Duke of Edinburgh.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was christened Charles Philip Arthur George on 15 December in the Music Room at Buckingham Palace by the archbishop of Canterbury, Geoffrey Fisher.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He has three younger siblings: Anne (born 1950), Andrew (born 1960), and Edward (born 1964).
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] George VI died on 6 February 1952, after which Charles's mother acceded to the throne as Elizabeth II and he became heir apparent.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Under a charter issued by Edward III in 1337, and as the monarch's eldest son, he automatically assumed the titles of Duke of Cornwall and, in the Scottish peerage, Duke of Rothesay, Earl of Carrick, Baron of Renfrew, Lord of the Isles, and Prince and Great Steward of Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He attended his mother's coronation at Westminster Abbey on 2 June 1953.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] When Charles was five, Catherine Peebles was appointed as his governess to oversee his education at Buckingham Palace.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He began attending Hill House School in West London in November 1956, becoming the first heir apparent to be educated at a school rather than by private tutors.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He did not receive preferential treatment from the school's founder and headmaster, Stuart Townend, who encouraged the Queen to have Charles train in football, noting that boys on the pitch were never deferential to anyone.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles later attended two of his father's former schools: Cheam School in Hampshire from 1958, followed by Gordonstoun in Moray, where he began classes in April 1962.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He became patron of Gordonstoun in May 2024.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Jonathan Dimbleby's authorised 1994 biography described Elizabeth and Philip as physically and emotionally distant parents, and criticised Philip for disregarding Charles's sensitive nature, including insisting that Charles attend Gordonstoun, where he was bullied.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Although Charles reportedly referred to the school as "Colditz in kilts", he later praised Gordonstoun for teaching him "a great deal about myself and my own abilities and disabilities".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In a 1975 interview Charles said he was "glad" to have attended the school and that its "toughness" had been "much exaggerated".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 1966, Charles spent two terms at the Timbertop campus of Geelong Grammar School in Victoria, Australia, during which he visited Papua New Guinea on a school trip with his history tutor, Michael Collins Persse.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles later described his time at Timbertop as the most enjoyable part of his education.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] On returning to Gordonstoun, he became head boy, and left in 1967 with six GCE O-levels and two A-levels in history and French, at grades B and C respectively.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Reflecting on his schooling, Charles later remarked that he "didn't enjoy school as much as I might have", adding that he was "happier at home than anywhere else".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Breaking royal tradition, Charles proceeded directly to university after completing his A‑levels rather than joining the British Armed Forces.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In October 1967, he was admitted to the University of Cambridge to study archaeology and anthropology for the first part of the Tripos at Trinity College, Cambridge, later switching to history.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] During his second year he spent one term at the University College of Wales in Aberystwyth, studying Welsh history and Welsh language.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles became the first British heir apparent to earn a university degree, graduating from Cambridge in June 1970 with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree with lower second-class honours (2:2).
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Following standard practice, his BA was promoted to a Master of Arts (MA Cantab) in August 1975.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles was created Prince of Wales and Earl of Chester on 26 July 1958, although his investiture did not take place until 1 July 1969, when he was crowned by his mother in a televised ceremony at Caernarfon Castle.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The event was controversial in Wales amid rising Welsh nationalist sentiment.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He took his seat in the House of Lords the following year, delivering his maiden speech on 13 June 1974, the first royal to speak from the floor since the future Edward VII in 1884.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles increasingly undertook public duties, founding the Prince's Trust in 1976 and travelling to the United States in 1981.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In the mid-1970s he expressed interest in serving as Governor-General of Australia, following a suggestion by the Australian prime minister, Malcolm Fraser.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The proposal was ultimately abandoned owing to a lack of public enthusiasm.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles served in the Royal Air Force (RAF) and the Royal Navy during the 1970s.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] His military training began in 1969, in his second year at Cambridge, when he joined the Cambridge University Air Squadron and learned to fly the Chipmunk.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was presented with his RAF wings in August 1971.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] After the passing-out parade that September, Charles embarked on a naval career and undertook a six-week course at the Royal Naval College, Dartmouth.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He subsequently served from 1971 to 1972 on the guided-missile destroyer HMS *Norfolk*, and on the frigates HMS *Minerva* from 1972 to 1973 and HMS *Jupiter* in 1974.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] That same year he qualified as a helicopter pilot at RNAS Yeovilton, and during his helicopter training completed commando instruction at the Commando Training Centre Royal Marines at Lympstone.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles then joined 845 Naval Air Squadron, a Royal Marines air support unit of the Fleet Air Arm, serving as a pilot aboard HMS *Hermes* and flying the Royal Marines commando variant of the Westland Wessex helicopter.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles spent his final ten months of active naval service commanding the coastal minehunter HMS *Bronington*, beginning on 9 February 1976.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He retired from active service later that year with the rank of Commander.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Two years later he undertook the parachute training course at RAF Brize Norton, having been appointed colonel-in-chief of the Parachute Regiment in 1977, and was a member of Parachute Course 841a.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles gave up flying after crash-landing a BAe 146 in Islay in 1994, when, as a passenger invited to fly the aircraft, he was at the controls; a board of inquiry found the crew negligent.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In his youth, Charles was romantically linked to several women.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] His girlfriends included Georgiana Russell, the daughter of Sir John Russell, who was the British ambassador to Spain; Lady Jane Wellesley; Davina Sheffield; Lady Sarah Spencer; and Camilla Shand, who later became his second wife.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles's great-uncle Lord Mountbatten advised him to "sow his wild oats and have as many affairs as he can before settling down", but, for a wife, he "should choose a suitable, attractive, and sweet-charactered girl before she has met anyone else she might fall for ...
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] It is disturbing for women to have experiences if they have to remain on a pedestal after marriage".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Early in 1974, Mountbatten began corresponding with 25-year-old Charles about a potential marriage to his granddaughter, Amanda Knatchbull.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles wrote to Amanda's mother, Lady Brabourne, who was also his godmother, expressing interest in her daughter.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Lady Brabourne replied approvingly, but suggested that a courtship with a 16-year-old was premature.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Four years later, Mountbatten arranged for Amanda and himself to accompany Charles on his 1980 visit to India.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Both fathers, however, objected: Prince Philip feared that his famous uncle would eclipse Charles, while Lord Brabourne warned that a joint visit would concentrate media attention on the cousins before they could decide whether to become a couple.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In August 1979, before Charles was due to depart alone for India, Mountbatten was assassinated by the Provisional Irish Republican Army.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] When Charles returned, he proposed to Amanda.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] But in addition to her grandfather, she had lost her paternal grandmother and younger brother in the bomb attack, and was now reluctant to join the royal family.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles first met Lady Diana Spencer in 1977, while he was visiting her home, Althorp.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was then the companion of her elder sister Sarah and did not consider Diana romantically until mid-1980.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] While Charles and Diana were sitting together on a bale of hay at a friend's barbecue in July, she mentioned that he had looked forlorn and in need of care at the funeral of Lord Mountbatten.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Soon, according to Dimbleby, "without any apparent surge in feeling, he began to think seriously of her as a potential bride" and she accompanied him on visits to Balmoral Castle and Sandringham House.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles's cousin Norton Knatchbull and his wife told Charles that Diana appeared awestruck by his position and that he did not seem to be in love with her.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Meanwhile, the couple's continuing courtship attracted intense attention from the press and paparazzi.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He proposed to Diana in February 1981, with their engagement becoming official on 24 February; the wedding took place at St Paul's Cathedral on 29 July.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Upon his marriage, Charles reduced his voluntary tax contribution from the profits of the Duchy of Cornwall from 50 per cent to 25 per cent.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The couple lived at Kensington Palace and Highgrove House, near Tetbury, and had two children: William, in 1982, and Harry, in 1984.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] As of 2025, Charles has an estranged relationship with his son Harry, who relinquished his royal family obligations and moved to the United States in 2020.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Within five years, the marriage was in trouble due to the couple's incompatibility and near 13-year age difference.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 1986 Charles had fully resumed his affair with former girlfriend, Camilla Parker Bowles.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Diana later commenced a relationship with Major James Hewitt, the family's former riding instructor.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles and Diana's evident discomfort in each other's company led to them being dubbed "The Glums" by the press.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Diana exposed Charles's affair with Parker Bowles in a book by Andrew Morton, *Diana: Her True Story*.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Audio tapes of her own extramarital flirtations also surfaced, as did persistent suggestions that Hewitt is Prince Harry's father, based on a physical similarity between Hewitt and Harry.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] However, Harry had already been born by the time Diana's affair with Hewitt began.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In December 1992, the British prime minister, John Major, announced the couple's legal separation in the House of Commons.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Early the following year, the British press published transcripts of a passionate, bugged telephone conversation between Charles and Parker Bowles that had taken place in 1989, which was dubbed "Tampongate" and "Camillagate".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles subsequently sought public understanding in a television film with Dimbleby, *Charles: The Private Man, the Public Role*, broadcast in June 1994.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In an interview in the film, Charles confirmed his own extramarital affair with Parker Bowles, saying that he had rekindled their association in 1986, only after his marriage to Diana had "irretrievably broken down".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] This was followed by Diana's own admission of marital troubles in an interview with journalist Martin Bashir on the BBC current affairs programme *Panorama*, broadcast in November 1995.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Referring to Charles's relationship with Parker Bowles, she said, "well, there were three of us in this marriage.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] So, it was a bit crowded." She also expressed doubt about her husband's suitability for kingship.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles and Diana divorced on 28 August 1996, after being advised by the Queen in December 1995 to end the marriage.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The couple shared custody of their children.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Diana died following a car crash in Paris on 31 August 1997.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles flew to Paris with Diana's sisters to accompany her body back to Britain.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 2003, Diana's butler Paul Burrell published a note that he claimed had been written by Diana in 1995, in which there were allegations that Charles was "planning 'an accident' in [Diana's] car, brake failure and serious head injury", so that he could remarry.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] She had allegedly expressed similar concerns in October 1995 to Lord Mishcon, her solicitor, that "reliable sources" had told her "that she and Camilla would be put aside" for Charles to marry Tiggy Legge-Bourke.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] When questioned by the Metropolitan Police inquiry team as a part of Operation Paget, Charles told the authorities that he did not know about his former wife's note from 1995 and could not understand why she had those feelings.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The allegations were later revealed to have been among the smears spread by Bashir to secure the interview with Diana for the BBC.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Because Charles and Parker Bowles were romantically involved periodically, both before and during their respective first marriages, their relationship received criticism from the public and the media.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Following both of their divorces, Charles declared his relationship with Parker Bowles was "non-negotiable" and appointed Mark Bolland to enhance Parker Bowles's public profile.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 2003, Parker Bowles moved into Charles's official residence, Clarence House and she accompanied Charles on almost all of his official events, including the annual Highland Games in Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Former Archbishop of Canterbury, George Carey, told *The Times* that Charles and Parker Bowles should marry, "He is heir to the throne and he loves her.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The natural thing is that they should get married." Their engagement was announced on 10 February 2005.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The Queen's consent to the marriage – as required by the Royal Marriages Act 1772 – was recorded in a Privy Council meeting on 2 March.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In Canada, the Department of Justice determined the consent of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada was not required, as the union would not produce any heirs to the Canadian throne.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles was the only member of the royal family to have a civil, rather than a church, wedding in England.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] British government documents from the 1950s and 1960s, published by the BBC, stated that such a marriage was illegal; these claims were dismissed by Charles's spokesman and explained by the sitting government to have been repealed by the Registration Service Act 1953.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The union was scheduled to take place in a civil ceremony at Windsor Castle, with a subsequent religious blessing at the castle's St George's Chapel.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The wedding venue was changed to Windsor Guildhall after it was realised a civil marriage at Windsor Castle would oblige the venue to be available to anyone who wished to be married there.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Four days before the event, it was postponed from the originally scheduled date of 8 April until the following day in order to allow Charles and some of the invited dignitaries to attend the funeral of Pope John Paul II.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles's parents did not attend the marriage ceremony; the Queen's reluctance to attend possibly arose from her position as Supreme Governor of the Church of England.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] However, his parents did attend the service of blessing and held a reception for the newlyweds at Windsor Castle.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The blessing by Archbishop of Canterbury Rowan Williams was televised.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Since their marriage in 2005, Charles has paid tribute to Camilla repeatedly in public letters, speeches and interviews, thanking her for "steadfast support" and referring to her as "my darling wife".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 1965, Charles undertook his first public engagement by attending a student garden party at the Palace of Holyroodhouse.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] During his time as Prince of Wales, he undertook official duties on behalf of the Queen, completing 10,934 engagements between 2002 and 2022.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He officiated at investitures and attended the funerals of foreign dignitaries.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles made regular tours of Wales, fulfilling a week of engagements each summer, and attending important national occasions, such as opening the Senedd.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The six trustees of the Royal Collection Trust met three times a year under his chairmanship.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles also represented his mother at the independence celebrations in Fiji in 1970, The Bahamas in 1973, Papua New Guinea in 1975, Zimbabwe in 1980 and Brunei in 1984.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 1983, a man named Christopher John Lewis, who had fired a shot with a .22 rifle at the Queen in 1981, attempted to escape a psychiatric hospital in order to assassinate Charles, who was visiting New Zealand with Diana and William.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] While Charles was visiting Australia on Australia Day in January 1994, David Kang fired two shots at him from a starting pistol in protest against the treatment of several hundred Cambodian asylum-seekers held in detention camps.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 1995 Charles became the first member of the royal family to visit the Republic of Ireland in an official capacity.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 1997 he represented the Queen at the Hong Kong handover ceremony.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] At the funeral of Pope John Paul II in 2005, Charles caused controversy when he shook hands with Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe, who had been seated next to him.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles's office subsequently released a statement saying that he could not avoid shaking Mugabe's hand and that he "finds the current Zimbabwean regime abhorrent".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles represented the Queen at the opening ceremony of the 2010 Commonwealth Games in Delhi, India.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In November 2010 he and Camilla were indirectly involved in student protests when their car was attacked by protesters.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In November 2013 he represented the Queen for the first time at a Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting, in Colombo, Sri Lanka.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles and Camilla made their first joint trip to the Republic of Ireland in May 2015.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The British Embassy called the trip an important step in "promoting peace and reconciliation".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] During the trip, he shook hands in Galway with Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Féin and widely believed to be the leader of the IRA, the militant group that had assassinated Lord Mountbatten in 1979.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The event was described by the media as a "historic handshake" and a "significant moment for Anglo-Irish relations".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Commonwealth heads of government decided at their 2018 meeting that Charles would be the next Head of the Commonwealth after the Queen.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The head is chosen and therefore not hereditary.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In March 2019, at the request of the British government, Charles and Camilla went on an official tour of Cuba, making them the first British royals to visit the country.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The tour was seen as an effort to form a closer relationship between Cuba and the United Kingdom.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles contracted COVID-19 during the pandemic in March 2020.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Several newspapers were critical that Charles and Camilla were tested promptly at a time when many National Health Service doctors, nurses and patients had been unable to be tested expeditiously.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He tested positive for COVID-19 for a second time in February 2022.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He and Camilla, who also tested positive, had received doses of a COVID-19 vaccine in February 2021.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles attended the November 2021 ceremonies to mark Barbados's transition into a parliamentary republic, abolishing the position of monarch of Barbados.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was invited by Prime Minister Mia Mottley as the future Head of the Commonwealth; it was the first time that a member of the royal family attended the transition of a realm to a republic.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In May of the following year, Charles attended the State Opening of the British Parliament, delivering the Queen's Speech on behalf of his mother, as a counsellor of state.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles acceded to the British throne on his mother's death on 8 September 2022.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He was the longest-serving British heir apparent, having surpassed Edward VII's record of 59 years on 20 April 2011.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles was the oldest person to succeed to the British throne, at the age of 73, surpassing the previous record holder, William IV, who was 64 when he became king in 1830.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles gave his first speech to the nation at 6 pm on 9 September, in which he paid tribute to his mother and announced the appointment of his elder son, William, as Prince of Wales.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The following day, the Accession Council publicly proclaimed Charles as king, the ceremony being televised for the first time.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Attendees included Queen Camilla, Prince William and the British prime minister, Liz Truss, along with her six living predecessors.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The proclamation was also read out by local authorities around the United Kingdom.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Other realms signed and read their own proclamations, as did Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland, the British Overseas Territories, the Crown Dependencies, Canadian provinces and Australian states.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In November 2022, the King and Queen hosted the South African president, Cyril Ramaphosa, during the first official state visit to Britain of Charles's reign.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The following March, they undertook a state visit to Germany, where Charles became the first British monarch to address the Bundestag.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Nonetheless, the coronation remained a Church of England rite, including the coronation oath, the anointing, crowning, investing with the regalia, and enthronement.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In July 2023, the royal couple attended a national service of thanksgiving at St Giles' Cathedral, where Charles was presented with the Honours of Scotland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] That same month, he asked for the profits from Britain's growing fleet of offshore wind-farms to be used for the "wider public good" rather than as extra funding for the monarchy, and it was announced that the monarchy's share of Crown Estate net profits would be reduced to 12 per cent.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In September, Charles became the first British monarch to give a speech from the French Senate chamber during a state visit to France.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The following month he visited Kenya, where he faced calls to apologise for colonial abuses; at a state banquet he acknowledged "abhorrent and unjustifiable acts of violence" but did not issue a formal apology.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In May 2024, the British prime minister, Rishi Sunak, asked the King to call a general election; subsequently, royal engagements that could divert attention from the election campaign were postponed.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In June 2024, Charles and Camilla travelled to Normandy to attend the 80th anniversary commemorations of D-Day.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The same month, the King received Emperor Naruhito of Japan during his state visit to the United Kingdom.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In July, the annual Holyrood Week, which is usually spent in Scotland, was shortened so that Charles could return to London and appoint a new prime minister following the general election.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] After Sunak's Conservative Party lost the election to the Labour Party led by Sir Keir Starmer, Charles appointed Starmer as prime minister.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In October 2024, the King and Queen toured Australia and Samoa; Australia was the first Commonwealth realm Charles visited since his accession.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In Samoa, he attended the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting for the first time as Head of the Commonwealth.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The tour was significantly scaled back owing to his cancer diagnosis, with a planned visit to New Zealand among the cancelled events.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles temporarily paused his cancer treatment during the tour.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In March 2025, the King received Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy at Sandringham House, just days after the Trump–Zelenskyy Oval Office meeting.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Zelenskyy later told *The Guardian* that Charles played a quiet but influential role in altering US president Donald Trump's attitude toward Ukraine.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The King and Queen initially cancelled a planned visit to Vatican City during their state visit to Italy, but on 9 April 2025 – their 20th wedding anniversary – they visited Pope Francis at Domus Sanctae Marthae as he was recovering from pneumonia.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The King, accompanied by the Queen, made his first visit to Canada as monarch in May 2025 at the invitation of Prime Minister Mark Carney, a trip that took place during a period of tension with the United States after President Trump made comments questioning Canada's sovereignty.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] During the visit, he opened the 45th Canadian Parliament and delivered the Speech from the Throne, the first time a Canadian monarch had done so in person since 1977.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In June 2025, the King approved the decommissioning of the British Royal Train ahead of its maintenance contract ending in 2027.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Described by the Keeper of the Privy Purse as part of a commitment to "fiscal discipline", the decision marked the end of 180 years of the royal family's use of a dedicated royal train.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In October 2025, during a state visit to the Holy See, Charles became the first British monarch to pray alongside a pope since the Reformation, joining Pope Leo XIV for a church service in the Sistine Chapel of the Apostolic Palace in Vatican City.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Later that month, Charles undertook his first official engagement in support of the LGBT+ community, unveiling "An Opened Letter", the UK's first national memorial honouring LGBT armed forces veterans, at the National Memorial Arboretum in Staffordshire.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] On 30 October, amid continuing controversy surrounding his brother Andrew's association with the American financier and child sex offender Jeffrey Epstein, Charles initiated a formal process to remove his style, titles and honours.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Following Andrew's arrest on 19 February 2026 on suspicion of misconduct in public office, the King expressed his "deepest concern" and stated that "the law must take its course".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In April 2026, during a state visit to the United States, Charles became the second British monarch to address a joint meeting of Congress, after his mother Elizabeth II in 1991.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] His speech received around a dozen standing ovations.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In May, he visited Golders Green after the previous month's stabbings, meeting victims at a Jewish Care charity centre, the Chief Rabbi, and members of the community's medical and security response teams.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In June, Buckingham Palace announced that the King would publish his personal tax bills, saying the move was intended to enhance "clarity and accessibility", making him the first head of state to do so.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In March 1998, Charles had laser keyhole surgery on his right knee and in March 2003, he underwent surgery at King Edward VII's Hospital to treat a hernia injury.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 2008, a non-cancerous growth was removed from his nasal bridge.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In January 2024, Charles underwent a "corrective procedure" at the London Clinic to treat benign prostate enlargement, which resulted in the postponement of some of his public engagements.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In February, Buckingham Palace announced that cancer had been discovered during the treatment, but that it was not prostate cancer.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Although his public duties were postponed, it was reported Charles would continue to fulfil his constitutional functions during his outpatient treatment.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He released a statement espousing his support for cancer charities and that he "remain[ed] positive" on making a full recovery.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In March, Camilla deputised for him in his absence at the Commonwealth Day service at Westminster Abbey and at the Royal Maundy at Worcester Cathedral.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He made his first major public appearance since his cancer diagnosis at the Easter service held at St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle, on 31 March.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In April 2024, it was announced that he would resume public-facing duties after making progress in his cancer treatment.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In March 2025, Charles was briefly admitted to hospital after experiencing temporary side effects from his cancer treatment.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He subsequently postponed several planned engagements.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In December, as part of the Stand Up to Cancer UK campaign hosted by Cancer Research UK and Channel 4, he announced that his treatment schedule would be reduced the following year.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The King's openness about his illness, contrasting with the traditionally guarded approach of earlier monarchs, was described by the media as unprecedented and as bringing him closer to the public.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] As early as 1985, Charles was questioning meat consumption.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In the *1985 Royal Special* television programme*,* he told the host, Alastair Burnet, that "I actually now don't eat as much meat as I used to.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In 2022, it was reported that he eats a breakfast of fruit salad, seeds, and tea.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He does not eat lunch, but takes a break for tea at 5:00 pm and eats dinner at 8:30 pm, returning to work until midnight or later.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Ahead of Christmas dinner in 2022, Charles confirmed to the animal rights group People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals that foie gras would not be served at any royal residences; he had stopped the use of foie gras at his own properties for more than a decade before becoming king.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] During a September 2023 state banquet at the Palace of Versailles, it was reported that he did not want foie gras or out-of-season asparagus on the menu.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Since founding the Prince's Trust in 1976, using his £7,500 of severance pay from the Royal Navy, Charles has established 16 more charitable organisations and now serves as president of each.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] King Charles III Charitable Fund has donated over £73 million to various causes since 1979.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] By September 2020 the Prince's Trust had supported over 1,000,000 young people and created 125,000 entrepreneurs.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] As Prince of Wales, Charles became patron or president of more than 800 other charities and organisations.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He received a Gold Blue Peter badge in 2023 for his environmental work and for his support of young people through the Prince's Trust.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The Prince's Charities Canada was established in 2010, in a similar fashion to its namesake in Britain.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles uses his tours of Canada as a way to help to draw attention to youth, the disabled, the environment, the arts, medicine, the elderly, heritage conservation and education.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] He has also set up the Prince's Charities Australia, based in Melbourne, to provide a co-ordinating presence for his Australian and international charitable endeavours.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles has supported humanitarian projects; for example, he has been known to donate his blood to raise awareness for health causes.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles and his sons took part in ceremonies that marked the 1998 International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles expressed strong concerns about the human rights record of the Romanian dictator Nicolae Ceaușescu.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] After Ceaușescu was deposed, he supported the FARA Foundation, a charity for Romanian orphans and abandoned children.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Charles has also supported humanitarian causes in Israel, including a private donation to the Peres Center for Peace and Innovation in 2020.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] Two of Charles's charities, the Prince's Foundation and the Prince of Wales's Charitable Fund (later renamed the King's Foundation and King Charles III Charitable Fund), came under scrutiny in 2021 and 2022 for accepting donations many in the media deemed inappropriate.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In August 2021 it was announced that the Prince's Foundation was launching an investigation into the reports, with Charles's support.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] The Charity Commission also launched an investigation into allegations that the donations meant for the Prince's Foundation had been instead sent to the Mahfouz Foundation.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In February 2022, the Metropolitan Police launched an investigation into the cash-for-honours allegations linked to the foundation, passing their evidence to the Crown Prosecution Service for deliberation in October.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p01] In August 2023 the Metropolitan Police announced that they had concluded their investigations and no further action would be taken.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] From young adulthood, Charles encouraged the understanding of Indigenous voices, saying they held crucial messages about preservation of the land, respecting community and shared values, resolving conflict, and recognising and making good on past iniquities.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He dovetailed this view with his efforts against climate change, as well as reconciliation between Indigenous and non-Indigenous peoples and his charitable work in Canada.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] At the 2022 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting Charles, who was representing his mother, raised that reconciliation process as an example for dealing with the history of slavery in the British Empire, for which he expressed his sorrow.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Letters sent by Charles to British government ministers in 2004 and 2005 expressing his concerns over various policy issues – known as the black spider memos – presented potential embarrassment following a challenge by *The Guardian* to release the letters under the Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In March 2015 the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom decided that Charles's letters must be released.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The Cabinet Office published the letters in May that year.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The reaction was largely supportive of Charles, with little criticism of him; the press variously described the memos as "underwhelming" and "harmless", and concluded that their release had "backfired on those who seek to belittle him".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] It was revealed in the same year that Charles had access to confidential Cabinet papers.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In October 2020, a letter sent by Charles to the Governor-General of Australia, Sir John Kerr, after Kerr's dismissal of Prime Minister Gough Whitlam in 1975, was released as part of the collection of palace letters regarding the Australian constitutional crisis.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In the letter, Charles was supportive of Kerr's decision, writing that what Kerr "did last year was right and the courageous thing to do".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In Charles's 1989 book *A Vision of Britain*, and in speeches and essays, he has been critical of modern architecture, arguing that traditional designs and methods should guide contemporary ones.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He has continued to campaign for traditional urbanism, human scale, restoration of historic buildings, and sustainable design despite criticism in the press.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Two of his charities – the Prince's Regeneration Trust and the Prince's Foundation for Building Community, which were later merged into one charity – promote his views.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The village of Poundbury was built on land owned by the Duchy of Cornwall to a master plan by Léon Krier, under the guidance of Charles and in line with his philosophy.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2013 developments for the suburb of Nansledan began on the estate of the Duchy of Cornwall with Charles's endorsement.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles helped purchase Dumfries House and its complete collection of 18th century furnishings in 2007, taking a £20 million loan from his charitable trust to contribute towards the £45 million cost.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The house and gardens remain property of the Prince's Foundation and serve as a museum and community and skills training centre.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] This led to the development of Knockroon, called the "Scottish Poundbury".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2025, it was reported that the design of a new generation of British towns would incorporate Charles's architectural ideas.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] After lamenting in 1996 the unbridled destruction of many of Canada's historic urban cores, Charles offered his assistance to the Department of Canadian Heritage in creating a trust modelled on Britain's National Trust, a plan that was implemented with the passage of the federal budget in 2007.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 1999 Charles agreed to the use of his title for the Prince of Wales Prize for Municipal Heritage Leadership, awarded by the National Trust for Canada to municipal governments that have committed to the conservation of historic places.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Whilst visiting the US and surveying the damage caused by Hurricane Katrina, Charles received the National Building Museum's Vincent Scully Prize in 2005 for his efforts in regard to architecture; he donated US$25,000 of the prize money towards restoring storm-damaged communities.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] For his work as patron of New Classical architecture, Charles was awarded the 2012 Driehaus Architecture Prize from the University of Notre Dame.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles has occasionally intervened in projects that employ architectural styles such as modernism and functionalism.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2009 he wrote to the Qatari royal family – the financier of the redevelopment of the Chelsea Barracks site – labelling Lord Rogers's design for the site "unsuitable".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Rogers claimed that Charles had also intervened to block his designs for the Royal Opera House and Paternoster Square.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] CPC Group, the project developer, took a case against Qatari Diar to the High Court.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] After the suit was settled, the CPC Group apologised to Charles "for any offence caused ... during the course of the proceedings".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Since the 1970s, Charles has promoted environmental awareness.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] At the age of 21 he delivered his first speech on environmental issues in his capacity as the chairman of the Welsh Countryside Committee.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles was named one of Time Magazine's 100 most influential climate leaders of 2025.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] An avid gardener, Charles has also emphasised the importance of talking to plants, stating that "I happily talk to the plants and trees, and listen to them.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] His interest in gardening began in 1980 when he took over the Highgrove estate.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] His "healing garden", based on sacred geometry and ancient religious symbolism, went on display at the Chelsea Flower Show in 2002.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles became involved with farming and various industries within it, regularly meeting with farmers to discuss their trade.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] A prominent critic of the practice, Charles has also spoken against the use of genetically modified crops, and in a letter to Tony Blair in 1998 he criticised the development of genetically modified foods.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The Sustainable Markets Initiative – a project that encourages putting sustainability at the centre of all activities – was launched by Charles at the World Economic Forum's annual meeting in Davos in January 2020.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In May of the same year, the initiative and the World Economic Forum initiated the Great Reset project, a five-point plan concerned with enhancing sustainable economic growth following the global recession caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The holy chrism oil used at Charles's coronation was vegan, made from oils of olive, sesame, rose, jasmine, cinnamon, neroli and benzoin, along with amber and orange blossom.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] His mother's chrism oil contained animal-based oils.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles delivered a speech at the 2021 G20 Rome summit, describing COP26 as "the last chance saloon" for preventing climate change and asking for actions that would lead to a green-led, sustainable economy.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In his speech at the opening ceremony for COP26, he repeated his sentiments from the previous year, stating that "a vast military-style campaign" was needed "to marshal the strength of the global private sector" for tackling climate change.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2022, the media alleged that Liz Truss had advised Charles against attending COP27, to which advice he agreed.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2010, he funded the Prince's Countryside Fund (renamed the Royal Countryside Fund in 2023), a charity that aims for a "confident, robust and sustainable agricultural and rural community".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles has controversially championed alternative medicine, including homeopathy.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He first publicly expressed his interest in the topic in December 1982, in an address to the British Medical Association.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] This speech was seen as "combative" and "critical" of modern medicine and was met with anger by some medical professionals.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Similarly, the Prince's Foundation for Integrated Health (FIH) attracted opposition from the scientific and medical community over its campaign encouraging general practitioners to offer herbal and other alternative treatments to NHS patients.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In April 2008, *The Times* published a letter from Edzard Ernst, professor of complementary medicine at the University of Exeter, which asked the FIH to recall two guides promoting alternative medicine.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] That year, Ernst published a book with Simon Singh called *Trick or Treatment: Alternative Medicine on Trial* and mockingly dedicated to "HRH the Prince of Wales".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The last chapter is highly critical of Charles's advocacy of complementary and alternative treatments.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles's Duchy Originals produced a variety of complementary medicinal products, including a "Detox Tincture" that Ernst denounced as "financially exploiting the vulnerable" and "outright quackery".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles personally wrote at least seven letters to the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency shortly before it relaxed the rules governing labelling of such herbal products, a move that was widely condemned by scientists and medical bodies.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] It was reported in October 2009 that Charles had lobbied the health secretary, Andy Burnham, regarding greater provision of alternative treatments in the NHS.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Following accounting irregularities, the FIH announced its closure in April 2010.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The FIH was re-branded and re-launched later in 2010 as the College of Medicine, of which Charles became a patron in 2019.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] From his youth until 2005, Charles was an avid player of competitive polo.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles also frequently took part in fox hunting until the sport was banned in the United Kingdom, also in 2005.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] By the late 1990s opposition to the activity was growing when Charles's participation was viewed as a "political statement" by those who were opposed to it.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles suffered several polo- and hunting-related injuries throughout the years, including a two-inch scar on his left cheek in 1980, a broken arm in 1990, a torn cartilage in his left knee in 1992, a broken rib in 1998, and a fractured shoulder in 2001.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles has been a keen salmon angler since youth and supported Orri Vigfússon's efforts to protect the North Atlantic salmon.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He frequently fishes the River Dee in Aberdeenshire, and claims his most special angling memories are from his time spent in Vopnafjörður, Iceland.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Apart from hunting, Charles has also participated in target rifle competitions, representing the House of Lords in the Vizianagram Match (Lords vs.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He became President of the British National Rifle Association in 1977.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles has been involved in performance since his youth, and appeared in sketches and revues while studying at Cambridge.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2000 he revived the tradition of appointing an official harpist to the Prince of Wales, in order to foster Welsh talent at playing the national instrument of Wales.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The role, now referred to as King's Harpist, is currently held by Mared Pugh Evans.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles is a keen watercolourist, having published books on the subject and exhibited and sold a number of his works to raise money for charity; in 2016 it was estimated that he had sold lithographs of his watercolours for a total of £2 million from a shop at his Highgrove House residence.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] For his 50th birthday 50 of his watercolours were exhibited at Hampton Court Palace and, for his 70th birthday, his works were exhibited at the National Gallery of Australia.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles founded the Royal Drawing School in 2000, which offers drawing classes to children and the public.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2001, 20 lithographs of his watercolour paintings illustrating his country estates were exhibited at the Florence International Biennale of Contemporary Art and 79 of his paintings were put on display in London in 2022.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] To mark the 25th anniversary of his investiture as Prince of Wales in 1994, the Royal Mail issued a series of postage stamps that featured his paintings.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles is the author of several books and has contributed a foreword or preface to numerous books by others.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He has also been featured in a variety of documentary films.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Shortly after his accession to the throne, Charles publicly described himself as "a committed Anglican Christian"; at age 16, during Easter 1965, he had been confirmed into the Anglican Communion by Archbishop of Canterbury Michael Ramsey in St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The King is the Supreme Governor of the Church of England and a member of the Church of Scotland; he swore an oath to uphold that church immediately after he was proclaimed King.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He attends services at various Anglican churches close to Highgrove and attends the Church of Scotland's Crathie Kirk with the rest of the royal family when staying at Balmoral Castle.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Laurens van der Post became a friend of Charles in 1977; he was dubbed Charles's "spiritual guru" and was godfather to Prince William.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] From van der Post, Charles developed a focus on philosophy and an interest in other religions.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles expressed his philosophical views in his 2010 book, *Harmony: A New Way of Looking at Our World*, which won a Nautilus Book Award.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles also attended the consecration of Britain's first Syriac Orthodox cathedral, St Thomas Cathedral, Acton.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles is patron of the Oxford Centre for Islamic Studies at the University of Oxford and attended the inauguration of the Markfield Institute of Higher Education, which is dedicated to Islamic studies in a multicultural context.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He stated in 2015 that he would retain the title of *Defender of the Faith*, whilst "ensuring that other people's faiths can also be practised", which he sees as a duty of the Church of England.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] His inclusive, multi-faith approach and his own Christian beliefs were expressed in his first Christmas message as king.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In line with his multi-faith approach, Charles has served as a patron of the Council of Christians and Jews and of the Jewish Museum London.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Since his birth, Charles has received close media attention, which increased as he matured.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] It has been an ambivalent relationship, largely impacted by his marriages to Diana and Camilla and their aftermath, but also centred on his future conduct as king.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Described as the "world's most eligible bachelor" in the late 1970s, Charles was subsequently overshadowed by Diana.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] After her death the media regularly breached Charles's privacy and printed exposés.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Known for expressing his opinions, when asked during an interview to mark his 70th birthday whether this would continue in the same way once he is King, he responded "No.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] I do realise that it is a separate exercise being sovereign.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] So, of course, you know, I understand entirely how that should operate." In September 2025, *The Economist* analysed all Charles's public speeches over the past 30 years and concluded that he has mellowed over the past three decades.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2009, Charles was named the world's best-dressed man by *Esquire* magazine.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Fashion magazine *British GQ* described Charles as "the true guardian of traditional British menswear" in 2012 and named him one of the most stylish people of 2025.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Italian designer Donatella Versace once said Charles "is an archetype of style".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2023 the *New Statesman* named Charles as the fourth-most-powerful right-wing figure of the year, describing him as a "romantic traditionalist" and "the very last reactionary in public life" for his support of various traditionalist think tanks and previous writings.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He was also named one of the 100 most influential people of 2023 by *Time* magazine.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles and Camilla topped *Tatler*'s Social Power Index for 2022 and 2023.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] A 2018 BMG Research poll found that 46 per cent of Britons wanted Charles to abdicate immediately on his mother's death, in favour of William.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] However, a 2021 opinion poll reported that 60 percent of the British public had a favourable opinion of him.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] On his accession to the throne, *The Statesman* reported an opinion poll that put Charles's popularity with the British people at 42 per cent.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] More recent polling suggested that his popularity increased sharply after he became King.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] As of August 2025, Charles continues to hold majority support with an approval rating of 59 per cent, and 62 percent of the public say "he is doing a good job", according to YouGov.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 1994, the German tabloid *Bild* published nude photos of Charles that were taken while he was vacationing in Le Barroux; they had reportedly been put up for sale for £30,000.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Buckingham Palace reacted by stating that it was "unjustifiable for anybody to suffer this sort of intrusion".
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles, "so often a target of the press, got his chance to return fire" in 2002, when addressing "scores of editors, publishers, and other media executives" gathered at St Bride's Fleet Street to celebrate 300 years of journalism.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles and Camilla were named in 2011 as individuals whose confidential information was reportedly targeted or actually acquired in conjunction with the news media phone hacking scandal.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In 2023, *The Guardian* estimated Charles's personal wealth at £1.8 billion.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Most of this wealth, which he inherited from his mother, Elizabeth II, was exempt from inheritance tax.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Clarence House, previously the residence of the Queen Mother, has been Charles's official London residence from 2003, after being renovated at a cost of £6.1 million.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] He previously shared apartments eight and nine at Kensington Palace with Diana before moving to York House at St James's Palace, which remained his principal residence until 2003.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Highgrove House in Gloucestershire is owned by the Duchy of Cornwall, having been purchased for Charles's use in 1980, and which he rented for £336,000 per annum.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Since William became Duke of Cornwall, Charles is expected to pay £700,000 per annum for use of the property.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles also owns a property near the village of Viscri in Romania.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] As Prince of Wales, Charles's primary source of income was generated from the Duchy of Cornwall, which owns 133,658 acres of land (around 54,090 hectares), including farming, residential, and commercial properties, as well as an investment portfolio.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Since 1993, he has paid tax voluntarily under the *Memorandum of Understanding on Royal Taxation*, updated in 2013.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Her Majesty's Revenue and Customs were asked in December 2012 to investigate alleged tax avoidance by the Duchy of Cornwall.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The Duchy was named in the Paradise Papers, a set of confidential electronic documents relating to offshore investment that were leaked to the German newspaper *Süddeutsche Zeitung* in 2017.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In the 2021–22 financial year, Charles received £23 million from the Duchy of Cornwall and paid a voluntary income tax of £5.9 million.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In June 2026, Charles revealed that he had paid £12.9 million in tax for the 2024–25 financial year, and it was also announced that, once the renovations at Buckingham Palace are completed, he and Camilla will not be moving into the palace.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles has held many titles and honorary military positions throughout the Commonwealth, is sovereign of many orders in his own countries and has received honours and awards from around the world.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In each of his realms he has a distinct title that follows a similar formula: *King of Saint Lucia and of His other Realms and Territories* in Saint Lucia, *King of Australia and His other Realms and Territories* in Australia, etc.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In the Isle of Man, which is a Crown Dependency rather than a separate realm, he is known as Lord of Mann.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles is also styled *Defender of the Faith*.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] There had been speculation throughout Elizabeth II's reign as to what regnal name Charles would choose upon his accession; instead of *Charles III*, he could have chosen to reign as *George VII* or used one of his other given names.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] It was reported that he might use George in honour of his grandfather George VI and to avoid associations with previous controversial kings named Charles.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles's office asserted in 2005 that no decision had yet been made.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Speculation continued for a few hours following his mother's death, until Prime Minister Liz Truss announced and Clarence House confirmed that Charles had chosen the regnal name *Charles III*.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] Charles, who left active military service in 1976, was awarded the highest rank in all three armed services in 2012 by his mother: Admiral of the Fleet, Field Marshal, and Marshal of the Royal Air Force.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] When Charles became king, he inherited the royal coats of arms of the United Kingdom and of Canada.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The design of his royal cypher, featuring a depiction of the Tudor Crown instead of St Edward's Crown, was revealed on 27 September 2022.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The College of Arms envisaged that the Tudor crown will be used in new arms, uniforms and crown badges as they are replaced.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] On 10 October 2024, designed by artist Timothy Noad, the new Royal Arms, alongside the new Lesser Arms, used by the UK government were officially unveiled, with both arms reflecting the stylistic changes made after Charles's accession.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The banners used by Charles as Prince of Wales varied depending upon location.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] His personal standard for the United Kingdom was the Royal Standard of the United Kingdom differenced as in his arms, with a label of three points *argent* and the escutcheon of the arms of the Principality of Wales in the centre.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] It was used outside Wales, Scotland, Cornwall and Canada, and throughout the entire United Kingdom when Charles was acting in an official capacity associated with the British Armed Forces.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The personal flag for use in Wales was based upon the Royal Badge of Wales.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In Scotland the personal banner used between 1974 and 2022 was based upon three ancient Scottish titles: Duke of Rothesay (heir apparent to the King of Scots), High Steward of Scotland, and Lord of the Isles.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] In Cornwall, the banner was the arms of the Duke of Cornwall.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The royal standard of the United Kingdom is used to represent the King in the United Kingdom and on official visits overseas, except in Australia and Canada.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] It is the royal arms in banner form undifferentiated, having been used by successive British monarchs since 1702.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] The royal standard of Canada is used by the King in Canada and while acting on behalf of Canada overseas.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] It is the *escutcheon* of the Royal Coat of Arms of Canada in banner form undifferentiated.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/charles-prince-of-wales-p02] As Prince of Wales, Charles wrote four books and was a co-author of other works.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] In 1997 the Hospice in Moray steering committee published their proposals for a day hospice in Moray, and £2.2 million was raised by Macmillan Cancer Support towards the creation of The Oaks.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] The facility was built in a leafy setting, using extensive timber-cladding and with colourful planting.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] It was officially opened by Prince Charles, Duke of Rothesay on 5 August 2003.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] It was awarded a Macmillan Quality Environment Mark (MQEM) in 2010, recognising the high standards in building design.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] An extension was opened in 2011, providing a larger lounge and dining area.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] The Oaks is a purpose-built unit to provide specialist care and support for people with cancer and other progressive illnesses in Moray.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] The Centre focuses on the control of pain and symptoms with the aim of reducing suffering and improving quality of life.
[src:the-oaks-elgin/the-oaks-elgin] It is situated in its own grounds approx ½ mile from Dr Gray's Hospital on the main A96 towards Inverness.
